      <emotional-journey>
        <reasoning>POV feelings and why: Kira experiences a rapid emotional arc: stunned anticipation and technical hope at the moment of contact (this is the payoff they’ve been waiting for), immediately followed by a complicated hollow ambivalence when the impending rescue threatens the fragile belonging she’s built with the plant community. By the end of the passage she begins to move toward quiet clarity — accepting that belonging, not species or origin, determines "home." Reader experience: readers share the initial exhilaration and suspense of contact, then feel a poignant, bittersweet tug as Kira’s expected joy is undercut by emotional conflict; finally the reader feels a gentle uplift as Kira’s emerging acceptance reframes the decision as existential (where do I belong?). Multiple beats vs. dominant tone: there are multiple distinct beats — (1) exhilarated anticipation/hope, (2) conflicted hollow/sad belonging, (3) settling acceptance/hope — with the second (ambivalence about leaving) providing the emotional pivot that gives the passage its depth. Comparison to prior pattern: the passage continues the story’s recurring anticipation→tension→acceptance arc (contact = payoff) but subverts the expected pure relief by layering in belonging and moral choice. Rather than repeating earlier rescue beats, this one deepens the emotional stakes by making rescue an ambiguous good; the pattern is familiar but enriched and thus not merely repetitive.</reasoning>
